 be operated by [[GateHouse Media]], a newspaper group owned by Fortress. News Corp. CEO and former ''Wall Street Journal'' editor [[Robert James Thomson]] indicated that the newspapers were \"not strategically consistent with the emerging portfolio\" of the company.<ref name=nybj-djlmgsale>{{cite news|title=News Corp. sells 33 papers to New York investors|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/newyork/news/2013/09/04/news-corp-sells-dow-jones-local-media.html|work=New York Business Journal|accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>  GateHouse in turn filed prepackaged Chapter 11 bankruptcy on September 27, 2013, to restructure its debt obligations in order to accommodate the acquisition.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-27/gatehouse-files-for-bankruptcy-as-part-of-fortress-plan.html | work=Bloomberg | title=GateHouse Files for Bankruptcy as Part of Fortress Plan}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent employees==\n'''Avrom \"Al\" Romm''' (1926\u20131999), named city editor of the ''Daily Record'' in 1957, became the ''Times Herald-Record'' first [[managing editor]] after the merge in 1960, a position he held until he was named editorial page editor in 1976. His youngest son is climate expert [[Joseph J. Romm]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.romm.org/obit.html|title=Record's first editor dies| first=Barbara| last= Bedell| newspaper=Times Herald-Record|date=December 1999}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Malcolm Browne]]''', who later won the [[Pulitzer Prize]] covering the [[Vietnam War]] for the [[Associated Press]].<ref name=\"WBurkhart\"/>\n\n'''Manny Fuchs''' (1924\u20132005) joined the ''Daily Record'' in 1957 and became chief photographer in 1960.<ref>Farlekas, Chris; July 10, 2005; [http://archive.recordonline.com/archive/2005/07/10/cffuchsw.htm  A salute to Manny Fuchs] July 10, 2005; ''Times Herald-Record''</ref>  He was a concentration camp survivor who became a photojournalist.<ref>[http://www.spysoftball.com/auschwitz.htm A Place Called Auschwitz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061210023950/http://www.spysoftball.com/auschwitz.htm |date=2006-12-10 }} Rayburn Hesse; March 9, 1993</ref> Before and during his stint at the ''Record'', he photographed [[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Tennessee Williams]], and [[Ben Hecht]], among others.  In 1966, he went to Vietnam to take pictures of hometown soldiers in the war zone.  In addition to his photojournalism assignments, he was a patient teacher<ref>Bedell, Barbara; March 19, 2003; [http://archive.recordonline.com/archive/2003/03/19/bed19.htm Columnist celebrates 30th anniversary]; ''Times Herald-Record''</ref> but hard taskmaster.  After retiring, he and his wife returned to her native France and lived in Paris, but came back to Middletown where they lived until his death in 2005.\n\n'''Glenn Doty''', one of the paper's former [[managing editor]]s, later trained hundreds of student journalists at ''The Legislative Gazette'', a student-run newspaper covering state government in [[Albany, New York|Albany]] operated jointly by [[State University of New York|SUNY]] campuses at [[State University of New York at New Paltz|New Paltz]] and [[State University of New York at Albany|Albany]].\n\n'''[[Hunter S. Thompson]]''', the future creator of [[gonzo journalism]] was fired by Editor A.N. Romm after \"kicking open the office candy machine with his bare feet - again.\"<ref name=\"WBurkhart\"/>\n\n'''[[Mike Levine (newspaper writer)]]''' (1952\u20132007), began as a columnist in 1983, working his way up to executive editor in 1999. After a year's hiatus in 2001, he became executive editor in 2002.<ref>[http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070115/NEWS/70115002 Obituary: Mike Levine] January 15, 2007</ref> The Mike Levine Journalism Education Fund was founded after his death, and sponsors an annual training for aspiring writers at The Mike Levine Workshop.<ref>[http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/]</ref> The workshop is led each year by prominent writers.<ref>[http://catskillmountaininn.com/spotlight-mike-levine-workshop/]</ref> In addition, an annual Mike Levine Column Read-a-Thon is held which raises money for the Education Fund.<ref>[http://mikelevineworkshop.org/readathon.pdf]</ref> Levine is the first writer in the history of ''The Record'' for whom every article he had written is available online by archive <ref>[http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/index.php?section=13]</ref> A clip of Levine addressing his community is on YouTube.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uv5YFq8dLlk]</ref>\n\n[[Mark Pittman]] (1957-2009), former Metro-Editor until 1997 when he left to work for Bloomberg News to break international headlines as a reporter who called the financial crisis of 2007.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Journalism|Hudson Valley}}\n*[http://www.recordonline.com/ Official website]\n*{{cite book|first=Franklin B.|last= Williams| title=Middletown a Biography| url=http://www.wkfinetools.com/hUS-saws/MSW-WMC/envir/1928-Middletown-Biography/0_img-pdf/1928-Middletown-aBiography-s.pdf#page175| pages=175\u2013181| year=1928| location=Middletown N.Y.}}\n\n{{Gannett}}\n\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Gannett publications]]\n[[Category:Media in Orange County, New York]]\n[[Category:Sullivan County, New York]]\n[[Category:Middletown, New York]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "67.210.40.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_Herald-Record"}
